segments.text: Okay.
One of the most educational lessons that I believe that I ever observed in my life on the ranch was down on Pepper Bluff.
There's only one passage up that bluff that you could get over it and get to the Three Springs Passage.
Horseback.
And you had to go around the point of the bluff, and if you didn't have a sure-footed horse, you're...
just as sure to get dunked in that hole of water, which was about 10 to 20 feet deep as you were for, dime was for a ginger snapper.
Now that was regular, but that was the only way we could get there.
And we'd go up this bluff and
go to Three Springs Pasture to gather the cattle to bring back.
We didn't bring them back that way.
We'd have to take them a mile and a half to two miles up the river to cross them.
Now that was real work.
And you knew what you had to do, and you didn't ask questions.
But we came around the point of Pepper Bluff, which
Definitely the water comes right up to the bluff itself, and you bring your horse right down at the edge of it, and the rock slants into the water, and it's slick as owl's grease.
And if you're not very careful, and you must give your horse its own time.
Don't kick him.
Don't spur him.
Let him feel his way and let him be a sure-footed person.
He's got more sense about that than you have.
Right.
So let him go.
And we got around this point, and I saw an old mama coon, and I hollered at my daddy, and he took his finger up to my mouth and he shook it to be quiet.
Mm-hmm.
And I went on over to where he was.
He said, I want to show you something.
All right, she came up this trail, and she had four babies behind her.
Oh, yeah.
And she got up to this pond.
I said pond.
She got up to this hole of water.
Mm-hmm.
And just before you get to this real deep hole, there was an eddy water hole out at the side, which was about, oh, I guess maybe 12 inches deep.
But you could see the fish running in it, and you could see lots of minnows, great big red-hossed minnows.
And we were way back, not way back, but we were...
I guess we were about 25 or 30 feet back and there was a big rock in front of us.
So we put our horses there and my daddy told me to get on top of this rock so I could watch all the maneuvering.
So the old mama coon

raccoon yeah but we call them coons out here comes up this trail and she gets to this hole this eddy water and she takes number one and sets him and she just takes him with both hands with her front feet and just socks him down on that ground just like he'd been bad and she

chattered something of course she chattered to him which to me meant you sit there she gets number two and sets him number three and she gets number four and she takes him behind these babies comes over here and she goes into this water and she catches um
Red Horse Minnow.
And she has it in both paws when she gets out.
And she gets down.
and puts it in her mouth, and she just shakes it and shakes it in this water.
Then she takes both hands and washes it and feeds this baby over here.
She goes back and she puts this baby way over here, away from the rest of them.
She goes back and she gets this other baby and moves him up, and she chatters and chatters.
She goes in...
And she gets another one.
This time she gets a perch.
She brings back.
She catches it.
And you'd be surprised.
She dives down in under and comes up.
It's fantastic to see how she does.
Catches them with her paws.
Yes.
And brings them out.
And then...
Number three was smart.
There's always got to be a smart aleck in every group.
So he goes up and gets ahead of her and goes in.
Man, she got him, she brought him back out of that thing and she just shook him just like you would shake somebody with her two front feet.
Just shook him good and popped him down and he didn't get one.
until she fed the next one.
And then she finally fed him.
And to me, that was one of the greatest lessons that I have ever learned in that you mind your parents, and you take what they give you, whether it's first or last.
She's calling.
Did you get that animal fed?
Uh-huh.
Go see her stomach.
I bet it's full all right.
Well, thank you, sweetheart.
Okay.
I'll see you.
Okay.
Okay.
But that to me was one of the greatest lessons.
Uh-huh.
I mean, even animals are taught to obey their parents.
Even animals are taught certain things that will help them.
That society of the animal world is real.
Absolutely.
The family structure is real.
That's right.
And where are we?
What are we doing to our family structure?
We're tearing it apart.
There isn't a family structure in this country anymore.
But it was with them.
I know.
All right.
What does...
When you take a Kildee, when you go down on the river and you get near her nest, she falls over.
She plays dead.
She flops and she winks and she cries.
Well, you know better.
If you know a Kildee, you know better, right?
If you know a Kildee, you know what's wrong, so you go on.
And she is attracting your attention.
Right, and pulling you.
And pulling you away from her baby.
I've had that happen.
That's mother instinct.
Mother instinct.
Oh, yes.
That's so true.
We're very close to that animal world, and we just don't like to think that sometimes.
We just don't like to recognize it.
But it's true.
Right.
All right.
Do you remember yesterday when I saw the twin deer, Fawn and the mama deer, the doe on the bank and they were down watering?
Uh-huh.
That head was working on a pivot.
Right.
Going back and forth, back and forth, watching.
Uh-huh.
She didn't make a noise.
She merely snorted.
And what did they do?
They moved.
All right.
A mother can stand out here at the side of the road and watching her child, and she'll scream 40 times for him to stop.
And he'll say, well, what do I have to do for her?
That's a breakdown in the chain of bonding.
That is exactly right.
That's a bonding break.
It really is.
A mother will stand and say, don't get out there in that street.
You're going to get run over.
Don't do that.
Well, why?
I want to go across the street.
But when that mama deer snorted one time, they left that water.
Yeah.
They did.
They really did.
They led the blue streak right up that hill.
They sure did.
They got out of the way.
We're above animal life.
We're supposed to be.
We are.
But what has happened to us?
We're not bonding with our children any longer.
That's right.
Not at all.
There's mothers and babies aren't bonding.
Fathers and babies aren't bonding.
No.
And unless you bond with your infant,
It's a very dangerous world.
It's worse than dangerous.
It's worse than dangerous.
Well, it's like the day was.
I know we really didn't have hospitalization for women, which is a marvelous thing because fewer women die in childbirth nowadays than they did back even in the 40s.
But I think there's a problem, in my opinion, is again that in the sterility of the American hospital, right now American gynecologists, Ava, are fighting to keep midwives from working in cities.
They don't want registered midwives.
People who've been nurse practitioners and nurses, they don't want women delivering women's babies anymore.
And I know you can tell me something about that.
I know that's very true.
I was quite a young girl, and 12 o'clock at night, we had no doctor here.
He had gone to a convention, and he wasn't here.
There was none at Blanco.
There was none at Fredericksburg.
This knock came to my door and said, Miss Ava, my wife's in labor, and we're having a baby, and I don't know what to do.
And I said, my land, man, I don't know either.
But I'll come.
I'll do what I can do.
So I went down there, and she was in labor.
My land, I'd never done anything like that.
Was this before you had your own?
Yes, it was long before I had.
See, we were married six years before Perky was born.
So this was about four years after we'd married.
I was about 22 years old.
Or hardly, maybe 21.
But I went on down there.
And I felt so sorry for that woman.
She was just really having a hard time.
And I said, well, honey, I don't know anything, but it looks to me like if you'd put your legs up in rafter shape in the bed and put your hands on them and push down on your legs,
It might help you.
I don't know anything about this, but maybe... You must have been terrified.
I was terrified, and I was afraid she was going to die, and I didn't know what in the world I would do.
I just was scared to death.
And I said, then keep pushing.
Well, the second time come around and push, well, out come Mr. Baby just really crying.
Well, there I was.
What do you do?
Mm-hmm.
What do you do in a case like that?
I didn't know about cutting a cord.
I knew the afterbirth was chained to it.
I knew if it wasn't taken care of at a certain time, that it would die.
And I knew if it wasn't cut off at a certain time, it'd bleed to death.
And I didn't know doodle and do.
And there wasn't any telephone.
There was two telephones on our street.
Two!
From the garage up to Klitz.
One at my house and one at Klitz.
And that was all the telephone.
So I said to him, I said, did you know anything about this?
And he was a father, and they'd had two before.
He said, I've had a doctor each time, and I don't know.
But they usually cut the cord and tie it.
And then the afterbirth will pass.
Oh, I said, oh, I don't know.
I don't know.
I just don't know what to do.
But anyway, I got a spring and I tied it.
I tied it on and then cut the cord.
It was just guesswork.
I really didn't know.
And I just kept saying, well, God, if you'll just give me the strength and tell me and help me out, just help me through this.
I tell you right now, there was a constant prayer going through my mind all the time because I just didn't know.
And there wasn't anything that we could do because there wasn't anybody we could get.
And so in a little bit, she passed after birth.
Well, all right.
Then I went ahead, cleaned up the baby, and clothed it, and put it back in her bed.
Then I cleaned her up and cleaned up the bed, which I had it pretty well padded already.
I didn't have any plastic.
I had oil cloth, which came off the table.
I got the table cloth and put under it so it wouldn't get on the bed or anything.
And I cleaned all that up.
and cleaned her up, and he was born on Halloween night.
Oh, my goodness.

But they got along just fine.

Ever delivered.
First one that I'd ever seen born.
I delivered lots of calves.
I delivered lots of little pigs.
and lots of lambs and goats, but I never delivered a baby.
That was something else.

Yes.

There was going to be babies.

from the other, but for the same token, these were animals, and this was a little life.

and a good woman, but they were poor.
They were honest, but poor.

I just perspired.

Did you ever deliver any more babies after that?
Oh, yes.

I was designated midwife for a long, long time.
I guarantee you that.
Now that's something.
That's something that we just don't see anymore.
You just don't see and you don't have to do it.
Unless it's a woman physician, women don't touch women anymore.
Oh, no.
You realize that?
No, no.
Women do not touch and help and deliver babies except in the poor communities.

Uh-huh.

That's right.

I think so.
That we just don't touch each other, we don't deliver our babies, we don't wipe the bodies clean before we bury them?
No, sir.
We don't touch each other?
Uh-uh.
Not anymore.

I think it's one of the biggest...

To me, it does.
To me, too.
I do believe that.
I really do.
